07655nam a22018855i 9780691233291DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20222022nju    fo  d z      eng d  a2021953502  a9780691233291  a(DE-B1597)612386  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 4aBM535b.M53 2022 7aHIS0370202bisacsh04a261.2/6090312231 aMichelson, Emily, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCatholic Spectacle and Rome's Jews :bEarly Modern Conversion and Resistance /cEmily Michelson. 1aPrinceton, NJ : bPrinceton University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (328 p.) :b11 b/w illus.  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA new investigation that shows how conversionary preaching to Jews was essential to the early modern Catholic Church and the Roman religious landscapeStarting in the sixteenth century, Jews in Rome were forced, every Saturday, to attend a hostile sermon aimed at their conversion. They were made to march en masse toward the sermon and sit through harsh policing, all the while scrutinized by local Christians, foreign visitors, and potential converts. In Catholic Spectacle and Rome’s Jews, Emily Michelson demonstrates how this display was vital to the development of early modern Catholicism.Drawing from a trove of overlooked manuscripts, Michelson reconstructs the dynamics of weekly forced preaching in Rome. As the Catholic Church began to embark on worldwide missions, sermons to Jews offered a unique opportunity to define and defend its new triumphalist, global outlook. They became a point of prestige in Rome. The city’s most important organizations invested in maintaining these spectacles, and foreign tourists eagerly attended them. The title of “Preacher to the Jews” could make a man’s career. The presence of Christian spectators, Roman and foreign, was integral to these sermons, and preachers played to the gallery. Conversionary sermons also provided an intellectual veneer to mask ongoing anti-Jewish aggressions. In response, Jews mounted a campaign of resistance, using any means available. Examining the history and content of sermons to Jews over two and a half centuries, Catholic Spectacle and Rome’s Jews argues that conversionary preaching to Jews played a fundamental role in forming early modern Catholic identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aJudaismxRelationsxCatholic Church. 7aHISTORY / Renaissance.2bisacsh  aAleksander (Hasidic dynasty).  aAlessandro Farnese (cardinal).  aAllusion.  aAnnales Ecclesiastici.  aBasilica di Santa Maria Maggiore.  aCalendar of saints.  aCalvinism.  aCanon law (Catholic Church).  aCardinal Vicar.  aCarmelites.  aCatholic Church.  aCatholic laity.  aCatholic theology.  aCatholicism.  aChaplain.  aChristian humanism.  aChristology.  aChurches of Rome.  aCollege of Cardinals.  aConfraternity.  aConversion of the Jews.  aConversion to Judaism.  aCopts.  aDeicide.  aDiocese.  aDowry.  aEpistle.  aFarce.  aFranciscans.  aFrequent confession.  aGiovanni Pico della Mirandola.  aGuido Reni.  aHagiography.  aHebrew alphabet.  aHeresy.  aHoly city.  aI Wish (manhwa).  aItalian Jews.  aJewish education.  aJewish mysticism.  aJewish studies.  aJews.  aJudaism.  aLutheranism.  aMartyr.  aMazel tov.  aMendicant.  aMessianism.  aMidrash.  aModern Rome.  aNeofiti.  aNorthern Italy.  aPamphlet.  aPapal appointment.  aPardes (Jewish exegesis).  aPassion Play.  aPersecution.  aPerugia.  aPeter Canisius.  aPhilo-Semitism.  aPiety.  aPonte Sisto.  aPope Clement VIII.  aPope Gregory XIII.  aPope Julius III.  aPope Leo